Castruccio et al. — "An Anisotropic Model for Global Climate Data"

arXiv:1906.11585
At the global scale, the paper argues, climatic variables are typically correlated at a shorter range in the latitudinal direction than in the longitudinal, and a fully isotropic kernel is inappropriate. The authors introduce axially symmetric Gaussian processes, where the covariance is stationary only in the longitude variable. This directly applies to  global (lat × lon) domain

Katzfuss & Guinness (2021) — "A General Framework for Vecchia Approximations of Gaussian Processes"

Statistical Science, 36(1):124–141
The Vecchia framework induces sparse precision matrices and frequently yields state-of-the-art accuracy in spatial applications. Vecchia approximation provides a balance between computational tractability and accuracy, making it a powerful tool for Gaussian process modeling in spatio-temporal fields — it offers a sparse Cholesky decomposition of the precision matrix. This is arguably the leading scalable GP method for large spatial/spatiotemporal datasets in statistics

